04890nam a2200673Ia 9781501725791DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20182005nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017257917 a10.7591/97815017257912doi  a(DE-B1597)515378  a(OCoLC)1091661850  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aRC451.Z55bJ33 2005 7aHIS0010402bisacsh04a362.2/1/00968912221 aJackson, Lynette, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSurfacing Up :bPsychiatry and Social Order in Colonial Zimbabwe, 1908–1968 /cLynette Jackson. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (248 p.) :b1 chart/graph/map, 1 table, 10 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCornell Studies in the History of Psychiatry00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Maps and Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tColonial and Postcolonial Place-Names -- tIntroduction. Colonial and Postcolonial Politics of Mental Health in Zimbabwe -- t1. "Lobengula's Wives Lived Here": The Colonization of Space and Meaning and the Birth of the Asylum in Southern Rhodesia -- t2. Bodies in Custody: Ingutsheni Lunatic Asylum, 1908-1933 -- t3. Black Men, White "Civilization," and Routes to Ingutsheni -- t4. Women Interrupted: Traveling Women, Anxious Men, and Ascriptions of Madness -- t5. Psychiatric Modernity in Black and White, 1933-1942 -- t6. The Africans Do Not Complain: The Monologue of Reason about Madness at Ingutsheni, 1942-1968 -- tEpilogue. Civilizing Mental Health Care: A Postcolonial Moment -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFocusing on the history of the Ingutsheni Lunatic Asylum (renamed a mental hospital after 1933), situated near Bulawayo in the former Southern Rhodesia, Surfacing Up explores the social, cultural, and political history of the colony that became Zimbabwe after gaining its independence in 1980. The phrase "surfacing up" was drawn from a conversation Lynette A. Jackson had with a psychiatric nurse who used the concept to explain what brought African potential patients into the psychiatric system. Jackson uses Ingutsheni as a reference point for the struggle to "domesticate" Africa and its citizens after conquest. Drawing on the work of Frantz Fanon, Jackson maintains that the asylum in Southern Rhodesia played a significant role in maintaining the colonial social order. She supports Fanon's claim that colonial psychiatric hospitals were repositories for those of "indocile nature" or for those who failed to fit "the social background of the colonial type."Through reconstruction and reinterpretation of patient narratives, Jackson shows how patients were diagnosed, detained, and deemed recovered. She draws on psychiatric case files to analyze the changing economic, social, and environmental conditions of the colonized, the varying needs of the white settlers, and the shifting boundaries between these two communities. She seeks to extend and enrich our understanding of how a significant institution changed the way citizens and subjects experienced the colonial social order.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aPsychiatric hospital carezZimbabwexHistoryy20th century. 0aPsychiatryxSocial aspectszZimbabwexHistoryy20th century. 0aSocial controlzZimbabwexHistoryy20th century. 0aSocial control. 4aAfrican Hist & Diaspora. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Africa / South / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172579140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501725791423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501725791/original  a978-3-1